metaData.descriptionCS: Working within a specified time limit, the examinee views a scale with missing weight(s) and selects the response option that keeps the scale balanced.

questions.title: Sample Item A
questions.correctInstructionsHTML:
Correct response [2]:

Say, That’s right. This one (point to response option 2) is the right color and the right shape, so you know it weighs the same as the red circle (point to red circle on scale). Let’s try some more.
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
Incorrect response:

If the child chooses response option 1, say, That’s not quite right. This one (point to response option 1) is a different color, so you don’t know that it weighs the same as this (point to red circle on scale). Which one of the others weighs the same as the red circle (point to red circle on scale)?

If the child chooses response option 3, say, That’s not quite right. This one (point to response option 3) is a different shape, so you don’t know that it weighs the same as this (point to red circle on scale). Which one of the others weighs the same as the red circle (point to red circle on scale)?

If the child chooses response option 4, say, That’s not quite right. This one (point to response option 4) is a different color and a different shape, so you don’t know that it weighs the same as this (point to red circle on scale). Which one of the others weighs the same as the red circle (point to red circle on scale)?

If the child chooses response option 5, say, That’s not quite right. Two red circles (point to response option 5) weigh more than one (point to red circle on scale). Which one of the others weighs the same as the red circle (point to red circle on scale)?

Regardless of the child’s performance, say, Let’s try some more.
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the scale and say, This scale has one red circle on this side (point to red circle on scale), but the other side is empty. Which one of these (point across response options) weighs the same as the red circle?

questions.title: Item 1
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Say, Which one of these (point across response options) weighs the same as this (point to left side of scale)?

questions.title: Item 2
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Which one of these (point across response options) weighs the same as this (point to left side of scale)?

questions.title: Item 3
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Which one of these (point across response options) weighs the same as this (point to left side of scale)?

questions.title: Sample Item B
questions.correctInstructionsHTML:
Correct response [2]:

Say, That’s right. The first scale shows that one yellow circle weighs the same as one yellow square. Let’s try some more.
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
Incorrect response:

If the child chooses response option 1, say, That’s not quite right. This scale shows that one yellow circle (point to yellow circle on first scale) weighs the same as one yellow square (point to yellow square on first scale). This one (point to response option 1) is a different color, so you don’t know that it weighs the same as this (point to yellow circle on first scale). Which one of the others weighs the same as the yellow square (point to yellow square on second scale)?

If the child chooses response option 3, say, That’s not quite right. This scale shows that one yellow circle (point to yellow circle on first scale) weighs the same as one yellow square (point to yellow square on first scale). This one (point to response option 3) is a different color, so you don’t know that it weighs the same as this (point to yellow circle on first scale). Which one of the others weighs the same as the yellow square (point to yellow square on second scale)?

If the child chooses response option 4, say, That’s not quite right. This scale shows that one yellow circle (point to yellow circle on first scale) weighs the same as one yellow square (point to yellow square on first scale). This one (point to response option 4) is a different shape, so you don’t know that it weighs the same as this (point to yellow circle on first scale). Which one of the others weighs the same as the yellow square (point to yellow square on second scale)?

If the child chooses response option 5, say, That’s not quite right. This scale shows that one yellow circle (point to yellow circle on first scale) weighs the same as one yellow square (point to yellow square on first scale). Two yellow circles (point to response option 5) weigh more than one (point to yellow circle on first scale). Which one of the others weighs the same as the yellow square (point to yellow square on second scale)?

Regardless of the child’s performance, say, Let’s try some more.
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the first scale and say, This scale shows that one yellow circle (point to yellow circle) weighs the same as one yellow square (point to yellow square). This scale (point to yellow square on scale with question mark) has one yellow square on this side. Which one of these (point across response options) weighs the same as the yellow square?
